# XIS Agent Notes

This repository treats Markdown documentation as the canonical knowledge source.

## Documentation Layers

- `README.md` is the public GitHub entry point for XIS users.
- `docs/user/*` is user-facing documentation. Organize it by public API behavior and workflows.
- `docs/user/advanced/*` is for optional or specialized capabilities. Do not present client-side storage as a core
  requirement; it is a convenience feature because applications can also keep state on the server.
- Module README files are mostly for framework developers and maintainers.
- `docs/framework/*` is cross-module maintainer documentation.
- `docs/agent/*` contains agent-specific rules.

## Source Material

The old documentation app lives in `docs-app` or `/Users/bernd/projects/xis-docs`. It is source material only. Do not
copy its structure blindly into Markdown.

When reconciling old and new documentation, merge them. The old documentation often has the better learning order and
contains explanatory material that must not disappear. The newer Markdown documentation may already contain corrected,
expanded, or newly tested behavior. Preserve newer correct material while restoring missing explanations and a
reader-friendly sequence from the old documentation.

Use `docs/framework/old-docs-coverage.md` as the migration checklist. After comparing an old chapter, do not leave a
generic `needs review` behind; mark the topic covered, deferred, obsolete, or record the concrete remaining product
decision.

## Runtime Sources For Template Documentation

When documenting XIS template behavior, verify the current runtime sources before treating old docs as authoritative:

- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/init/DomNormalizer.js`: framework elements, attribute syntax, and normalization
  between tag and attribute forms.
- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/init/HandlerBuilder.js`: which normalized elements and attributes receive runtime
  behavior, such as page links, frontlet links, action links, action buttons, forms, inputs, and submit controls.
- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/parse/ELFunctions.js`: built-in expression-language functions.

Use the old documentation app for editorial structure and examples, but use these runtime files to confirm what actually
exists.

## Template Completion Rule

Template behavior is only really done when all three layers agree:

- runtime code supports the behavior
- integration tests cover what the Java action/model side receives or renders
- `docs/user/*` explains the public behavior with copyable examples

For template features that exist in both forms, always think in pairs:

- attribute syntax, for example `<input xis:binding="name">`
- element syntax, for example `<xis:input binding="name">`

Both forms are worth testing because `DomNormalizer.js` can break one while the other still works.

For form controls, tests should assert what reaches the `@Action` method through `@FormData`, not merely that a DOM value
changed or a request-like payload was assembled. Repeated bindings are intentional: multiple controls with the same
binding can submit multiple values into a Java collection.

Validation styling is part of the template contract. `xis:error-class` can be used with `xis:binding`; labels and wrapper
elements can use `xis:error-binding` to point at a field without becoming form controls. `xis:error-style` applies an
inline style during the same error state. Selection highlighting uses a parent `xis:selection-group` (or plain
`selection-group`) and child `xis:selection-class` (or plain `selection-class`); multiple groups must remain independent.

Drag and drop is intentionally small: `xis:drag="from:${field}"` defines one named drag value, and
`xis:drop="move(from, target='${targetField}')"` calls a normal `@Action`. Prefer named Java parameters with
`@Parameter("from")` and `@Parameter("target")`. If users need multiple values, they should encode a simple
string themselves or write custom JavaScript. Keep docs and tests focused on this 80-percent case. In integration tests,
use `one.xis.test.dom.DragAndDrop(source, target).doDragAndDrop()` so tests exercise `dragstart`, `dragover`, `drop`,
and the shared `DataTransfer` payload.

For dynamic resource attributes that a browser loads immediately, use XIS-prefixed attributes such as `xis:src`.
`AttributeHandler` evaluates `xis:src`, removes the framework attribute, and writes the result to the real `src`; this
prevents requests for raw template expressions before XIS has initialized the page.

## Gradle Generation Tasks

The XIS Gradle plugin exposes two user-facing scaffolding tasks:

- `./gradlew xisTemplates` runs `XISTemplateProcessor` and creates missing HTML templates for `@Page` and `@Frontlet`
  controllers under `src/main/java`.
- `./gradlew xisTests` runs `XISTestProcessor` and creates missing `xis-test` integration-test skeletons for `@Page`
  controllers under `src/test/java`.
- `./gradlew xisValidate` runs `XISValidateProcessor` for XIS validation checks.

The plugin adds `one.xis:xis-test` as a real `testImplementation` dependency and configures Gradle `Test` tasks to use
JUnit Platform. `xis-test` exposes the JUnit API and AssertJ because generated tests import them. Both generation tasks
are safe to run repeatedly because processors do not overwrite existing files. Keep the processors and docs on current
public names: `Frontlet`, not the old `Widget` terminology.

The intended quickstart/TDD path is: create a page class, run `./gradlew xisTemplates xisTests`, edit the generated test to
describe the desired UI behavior, then implement controller/model/action/template code until the test passes.

For XIS Boot projects, keep the Gradle plugin tasks aligned: `xisJar` creates
`build/libs/<project-name>-<version>.jar`, and `xisRun` depends on that task and starts the generated jar.

When user docs show XIS dependencies in a build that applies `one.xis.plugin`, prefer versionless XIS dependency
coordinates such as `implementation "one.xis:xis-spring"`. The plugin aligns supported XIS module versions to its own
version. Keep explicit XIS versions only for examples that intentionally do not use the plugin.

## Client Storage Rule

`@LocalStorage`, `@SessionStorage`, and `@ClientStorage` are parameter annotations in the controller API. They are meant
for key-based exchange of selected browser-state values, not for sending the whole browser storage to the server.

The server derives the relevant storage keys from controller method parameters and writes those keys into the client
configuration. The client sends all configured keys for the current page/frontlet with a request, independent of whether
the currently invoked action actually uses every key. This avoids predicting controller behavior in JavaScript.

After a controller method runs, storage parameters are written back to the response so object mutations made inside the
action are stored in the browser. This is most natural for mutable DTO-like values; do not assume method return values
annotated with storage annotations are part of the public API unless the annotation target and tests confirm it.

## Security Documentation Rules

Security documentation must describe the concrete interfaces users implement, not only the concept. For local
authentication this means `UserInfoService`. For XIS as an OpenID Connect provider this means `IDPService`, including
client registration through `IDPClientInfo` and user/client linkage through `IDPUserInfo`.

Keep user documentation focused on direct user dependencies only:

- `xis-spring` for Spring applications
- `xis-boot` for standalone applications
- `xis-test` for lower-level user-facing integration tests only when the application does not use the XIS Gradle plugin
- `xis-boot-starter-test` for `@XisBootTest` and generated tests only when the application does not use the XIS Gradle plugin
- `xis-authentication` for protected pages, local login, and external OpenID Connect login
- `xis-idp-server` for running XIS as an OpenID Connect provider
- `xis-theme` for the optional default CSS/theme
- `xis-distributed` for Microfrontend Architecture and remote page/frontlet delivery
- `xis-sql` for JDBC repositories and SQL mapping
- `xis-mongodb` for MongoDB document repositories and change streams

Do not tell users to add transitive implementation modules such as `xis-idp-client`, `xis-controller-api`,
`xis-validation`, or `xis-context`. Those names belong in module README files or framework documentation, not in
`docs/user/*`.
When the XIS Gradle plugin is used, do not tell users to add `xis-test` or `xis-boot-starter-test`; the plugin configures
the matching test dependency.

When documenting XIS as IDP, mention that user code fills application claims while XIS fills technical token fields such
as `sub`, `iss`, `iat`, `exp`, `nbf`, and `client_id` during token creation.

Security changes should stay coupled to E2E coverage in `/Users/bernd/projects/xis-end-to-end-tests`. XIS-as-IDP is
covered there by a two-process setup: one XIS app runs as an OpenID Connect provider, another XIS app consumes it through
the normal external provider flow. The multiple-provider case combines that XIS IDP with a mock OpenID Connect provider
and must verify that the provider selection page offers both links and that choosing XIS completes the protected-page
login.

## Refresh Event Rules

Refresh events are a general UI refresh feature, not an SSO feature. SSO can use the same transport internally, but user
documentation and E2E tests should explain the normal application case first, such as a cart counter, dashboard tile, or
notification badge.

Keep these cases distinct in code, docs, and tests:

- `publishToAll` targets every connected client, anonymous or authenticated.
- `publishToClient` targets one browser client. This is not the same as a user.
- `publishToUser` targets all connected clients of one authenticated user and therefore requires authentication.
- `publishToAllUsers` targets authenticated clients only.

`FrontletResponse.reloadFrontlet(...)` is not a broadcast event. It is an action-response special case for refreshing
another already visible frontlet in the current browser. Do not describe it as needed for the current page or the
frontlet that handled the action; those are updated by the normal action response. Use it for a separate frontlet that is
not otherwise refreshed, for example a header cart summary after an action in a product-list frontlet.

For page actions, the normal action response refreshes the page and its visible frontlets. Do not process action
`updateEventKeys` or explicit frontlet reloads again after that page refresh, otherwise frontlets can load twice. For
frontlet actions, update events still matter because only the handling frontlet is refreshed automatically.

When changing refresh behavior, inspect both sides:

- controller-api/server: `RefreshEventPublisher`, `RefreshEvent`, and `RefreshTarget` are public controller API;
  `SseService`, `MainController`, and
  `ControllerWrapper`
- browser: `SseConnector`, `PageController.handleUpdateEvents`, `FrontletContainers.handleUpdateEvents`,
  `FrontletContainerHandler.handleActionResponse`, and `FrontletResponse.reloadFrontlet` handling

SSE connections must not silently stay dead. The browser reconnects closed `/xis/events` streams with backoff and also
checks configured event streams before normal XIS HTTP requests. A failed SSE reconnect must not swallow the HTTP
request; the normal request is still needed for the standard authentication/login flow. On the server, `/xis/events`
renews XIS tokens when possible and writes updated `access_token` and `refresh_token` cookies before opening the stream.
If token handling raises `AuthenticationException`, the SSE endpoint returns `401` and does not open a stream; do not
catch unrelated exceptions here, because real backend failures must remain visible.
If a terminal SSE error suggests that authentication may have expired, `SseConnector` asks the application for a
throttled authentication check. The application refreshes the current page, so only the normal HTTP `401 + Location`
handling can redirect to login. Do not redirect directly from `EventSource.onerror`; SSE errors can also be caused by
network sleep, reloads, or temporary server restarts.
Refresh event delivery is not allowed to silently drop events during short reconnect gaps. `SseService` tracks recently
known clients for a small TTL and queues events for `publishToClient`, `publishToUser`, and `publishToAll` when an
emitter is temporarily missing or closed. The TTL should stay aligned with the browser reconnect backoff: long enough
for reconnect, short enough to forget truly closed clients. The authoritative value is
`ClientConfigService.PENDING_EVENT_TTL_SECONDS`; the server queue window and the value sent to the browser in
`ClientConfig.pendingEventTtlSeconds` must not diverge.

## Distributed Application Rules

Distributed XIS applications route in two steps: the URL resolves to a page/frontlet entry in the client config, and that
entry may carry a remote host. The JavaScript client then calls the matching `/xis/*` endpoint on that host. Same-origin
components have no host and keep using relative URLs.

`xis-distributed` must own distributed runtime behavior. It provides the `ComponentHostResolver` bridge and a
configuration-aware CORS filter. Do not make the generic default CORS filter guess distributed topology; the distributed
filter should allow only origins that belong to `XisDistributedConfig.getAllowedOrigins()` or the current local URL.

The properties implementation uses public `frontlet` wording:

- `xis.remote.frontlet.<frontletId>=<host>`
- `xis.remote.frontlet-url.<frontletId>=<url>`
- `xis.remote.page.<normalizedPath>=<host>`
- `xis.remote.origin.<name>=<origin>`

Distributed topology should be exposed as maps (`getFrontletHosts`, `getFrontletUrls`, `getPageHosts`, and
`getAllowedOrigins`). The framework derives remote/local decisions from those maps. Do not write examples that require
the user to implement both maps and boolean checks. `DistributedComponentHostResolver` and `DistributedCorsFilter` copy
the configured maps/origins once at startup, so configuration implementations may perform expensive discovery there
without turning every request into a repeated lookup.

Page host mappings use normalized URLs as keys, for example `/product/*/details.html`, not page class names. This is
intentional because distributed applications should depend on public URLs rather than package names from another team.

Distributed SSO requires credentialed browser requests on both paths: XHR/fetch-style XIS calls and SSE event streams.
The client must open `/xis/events` not only on the shell origin but also on configured remote hosts, and all of those
connections must include credentials so remote `publishToUser(...)` events can identify the user.

End-to-end coverage lives in `/Users/bernd/projects/xis-end-to-end-tests` as
`:e2e-tests-core:distributedTest`. It starts two Boot runtimes, one shell/page process and one remote process, and
verifies a remote frontlet, remote-frontlet-to-remote-frontlet navigation by URL, and a remote page including actions
executed on the remote server.

## Theme Rules

`xis-theme` is a user-facing convenience module for developers with only basic HTML/CSS knowledge. Its promise is:
add the dependency and get acceptable prototype styling without explicit stylesheet links. Keep user documentation and
tests focused on that promise, not on internal theme implementation modules.

The theme resource contract is:

- `default-theme.css` provides the default CSS variables.
- `xis.css` provides structural CSS such as navigation, forms, and grid classes.
- application `theme.css` overrides variables and must be loaded after `xis.css`.
- application `theme-logo.svg` wins over `default-theme-logo.svg`.

E2E coverage for this lives in `/Users/bernd/projects/xis-end-to-end-tests` and should verify browser-observable
behavior: automatic CSS links, override order, custom logo loading, and grid positioning. Do not make these tests
pixel-perfect design snapshots; check the public contract.

## Example Discipline

Documentation examples are part of the public API.

When documenting public behavior:

- include copyable Java examples
- include matching HTML templates when relevant
- prefer examples that can become tests
- avoid pseudocode for annotation names, template attributes, and file locations

The long-term goal is that documented examples are executable or covered by the test suite.

## Collaboration Discipline

Treat user statements about desired documentation structure as strong input, not as unquestioned final architecture.
Check them against the codebase, the old documentation, and the reader's path. If the user points out a missing concept,
make sure it appears where a reader would naturally look, even if the detailed material lives on a separate page.

## Website Policy

A documentation website may be built later, including a project wizard. The website should render or import the
Markdown documentation instead of becoming a second manually maintained copy.
